## 6. Oblique Strategies

**Brian Eno** — Musician · Producer · Artist (UK)
**Peter Schmidt** — Multimedia Artist (Germany/UK)
*Oblique Strategies: Over One Hundred Worthwhile Dilemmas* (1975)

Eno is one of the most influential figures in modern music — pioneer of ambient music, producer of David Bowie, U2, Coldplay, Talking Heads. Schmidt was a painter and multimedia artist. Both independently developed sets of creative prompts; they merged them into a single deck of cards in 1974. The cards were most famously used during the recording of Bowie's Berlin triptych (Low, "Heroes", Lodger).

### The Framework: Constraint-Based Creative Disruption

Each card contains a single cryptic, aphoristic prompt. When stuck, draw one card and follow it. Examples from the deck:

- "Use an old idea"
- "Honor thy error as a hidden intention"
- "What would your closest friend do?"
- "Emphasize repetitions"
- "Do nothing for as long as possible"
- "Disconnect from desire"
- "Only one element of each kind"
- "Use unqualified people"
- "What is the reality of the situation?"
- "Make an exhaustive list of everything you might do and do the last thing on the list"
- "Into the impossible"
- "A line has two sides"
- "Breathe more deeply"

### Core Principles
- Constraints liberate creativity; total freedom paralyzes
- Disruption of habitual patterns is more valuable than optimization of them
- The prompt should be vague enough to force reinterpretation, specific enough to force action
- The emotional/irrational dimension of creativity is a feature, not a bug
- Serendipity can be systematized through structured randomness

### Maximum Seeking Alignment
Oblique Strategies is the inverse complement to TRIZ. Where TRIZ systematically narrows the solution space, Oblique Strategies deliberately explodes it. For a builder: when your architecture is over-determined and you're trapped in local optima, a single strange constraint can teleport you to a better region of the design space entirely.

